Therefore, I think the final answer is 9.37 x 10^5 m/s, which in the required format is \boxed{9.37 \times 10^5}. **Final Answer** \boxed{9.37 \times 10^5} </think> To determine the velocity of an electron ejected from the excited state \( n = 3 \) of a hydrogen atom after absorbing a photon with a wavelength of \( 3.091 \times 10^{-7} \) meters, we follow these steps: 1. **Calculate the energy of the photon:** \[ E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{hc}{\lambda} \] where \( h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s} \), \( c = 3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \), and \( \lambda = 3.091 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} \). \[ E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \times 3.00 \times 10^8}{3.091 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.425 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] 2. **Determine the work function for the excited state \( n = 3 \):** The energy of the \( n = 3 \) level in a hydrogen atom is: \[ E_3 = -\frac{13.6 \, \text{eV}}{3^2} = -1.511 \, \text{eV} \] Converting this to joules: \[ E_3 = -1.511 \, \text{eV} \times 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J/eV} = -2.42 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] The work function (absolute value) is \( 2.42 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \). 3. **Calculate the kinetic energy of the ejected electron:** \[ E_{\text{kinetic}} = E_{\text{photon}} - \text{Work function} \] \[ E_{\text{kinetic}} = 6.425 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} - 2.42 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} = 4.005 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] 4. **Determine the velocity of the electron:** Using the kinetic energy formula \( E_{\text{kinetic}} = \frac{1}{2}mv^2 \): \[ v = \sqrt{\frac{2E_{\text{kinetic}}}{m}} \] where \( m = 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg} \). \[ v = \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 4.005 \times 10^{-19}}{9.109 \times 10^{-31}}} = \sqrt{8.79 \times 10^{11}} \approx 9.37 \times 10^5 \, \text{m/s} \] Thus, the velocity of the ejected electron is \(\boxed{9.37 \times 10^5}\) m/s.
